            <div class="faq-container">
                <div class="accordion">
                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What is the difference between Thermal Engineering and Mechanical Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Thermal Engineering is a specialized branch of Mechanical Engineering that focuses specifically on heat transfer, thermodynamics, and energy systems. While Mechanical Engineering covers a broader range of topics including mechanics, materials, manufacturing, and design, Thermal Engineering delves deeper into the principles and applications of thermal sciences and energy conversion processes.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What skills are most important for a career in Thermal Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Key skills for thermal engineers include strong knowledge of thermodynamics, heat transfer, and fluid mechanics; proficiency in computational tools like CFD software and programming languages; analytical problem-solving abilities; and understanding of energy systems and efficiency. Additionally, skills in technical writing, project management, and familiarity with relevant industry standards and codes are valuable for career advancement.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

                    <div class="accordion-item">
                        <div class="accordion-header">What are the emerging areas in Thermal Engineering?</div>
                        <div class="accordion-content">
                            <p>Emerging areas include renewable thermal energy systems (solar thermal, geothermal), thermal energy storage technologies, waste heat recovery, thermal management of electronics and batteries, advanced cooling technologies, net-zero energy buildings, and computational thermal engineering using AI and machine learning. The integration of thermal systems with smart grids and IoT for optimization is also a growing field.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>

